Of course, this is a very famous (and easy) problem! We almost always guess the common difference, but how do you think to go about doing so? Let's ask for $a_2-a_1$. Clearly using the sum formula, we can say:
\begin{align*}
a_2-a_1 &=\frac{a_{100}-a_1}{99}\\
&=\frac{a_{100}-a_{50}}{99}
\end{align*}
Now,  $a_{100}-a_{50}$ is the sum of $50$ steps each of $a_2-a_1$. What is this? That is just a fraction of this larger sum - the sum of all $100$ lower terms! So:
\begin{align*}
a_{100}-a_{20}&=\frac{a_{100}-a_1}{2}\\
&=\frac{50\left(a_{100}-a_1\right)}{100}\\
&=\frac{1}{2}\left(a_{100}-a_1\right)
\end{align*}
Can you see how for a sum of $200$ we keep the same ratio? And if you think about it, the common difference is the same! Thus...
\begin{align*}
\frac{a_{100}-a_1}{99} &=\frac{\frac{1}{2}}{99}\\
&=\boxed{\frac{1}{198}}
\end{align*}
Answer: $\frac{1}{198}$
